"Fukushima T., Ozaki N., Kaminishi H., Harasawa H., Matsushige K.","Forecasting the changes in lake water quality in response to climate changes, using past relationships between meteorological conditions and water quality",2000,"Hydrological Processes","14","3",,"593","604",,,10.1002/(SICI)1099-1085(20000228)14:3<593::AID-HYP956>3.0.CO;2-O,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034723967&partnerID=40&md5=9491b0d258eb4221cd81225135d610cf","Dept. of Civ. and Environ. Eng., Faculty of Engineering, Hiroshima University, 1-4-1, Kagamiyama, Hiroshima, 739-8527, Japan; Natl. Inst. for Environ. Studs. 18-2, Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki, 305-0053, Japan","Fukushima, T., Dept. of Civ. and Environ. Eng., Faculty of Engineering, Hiroshima University, 1-4-1, Kagamiyama, Hiroshima, 739-8527, Japan; Ozaki, N., Dept. of Civ. and Environ. Eng., Faculty of Engineering, Hiroshima University, 1-4-1, Kagamiyama, Hiroshima, 739-8527, Japan; Kaminishi, H., Dept. of Civ. and Environ. Eng., Faculty of Engineering, Hiroshima University, 1-4-1, Kagamiyama, Hiroshima, 739-8527, Japan; Harasawa, H., Natl. Inst. for Environ. Studs. 18-2, Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki, 305-0053, Japan; Matsushige, K., Natl. Inst. for Environ. Studs. 18-2, Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki, 305-0053, Japan","In order to forecast the effects of global warming on the water environment, the relationship between meteorological conditions and lake water quality was investigated statistically using 17 years of monitoring data obtained from a shallow eutrophic lake, Lake Kasumigaura. The usefulness of the DPY (difference from the previous year) method was confirmed for removing the watershed change (e.g. land cover, population, etc.). From the analysis of the relationships between air temperature and water temperature on a monthly basis, the delay of time was seen to be negligible, but the gain was reduced due to the high frequency of change. As the amount of precipitation affected their relationship on a yearly basis, the slopes of 1.0-1.2°C water temperature/°C air temperature were determined with the DPY method by excluding the combinations of the years having large difference in annual precipitation. The deterioration of lake water quality, such as increases in COD (chemical oxygen demand) and decreases in transparency, was quantitatively assessed as corresponding to an increase in air temperature. In addition, we found that higher precipitation led to high nitrogen concentrations on a monthly basis, as well as on a yearly basis, probably induced by both the runoff of soilwater having high concentrations and the lowering of residence times of lake water. Copyright (C) 2000 John Wiley and Sons, Ltd.In order to forecast the effects of global warming on the water environment, the relationship between meteorological conditions and lake water quality was investigated statistically using 17 years of monitoring data obtained from a shallow eutrophic lake, Lake Kasumigaura. The usefulness of the DPY (difference from the previous year) method was confirmed for removing the watershed change (e.g. land cover, population, etc.). From the analysis of the relationships between air temperature and water temperature on a monthly basis, the delay of time was seen to be negligible, but the gain was reduced due to the high frequency of change. As the amount of precipitation affected their relationship on a yearly basis, the slopes of 1.0-1.2 °C water temperature/°C air temperature were determined with the DPY method by excluding the combinations of the years having large difference in annual precipitation. The deterioration of lake water quality, such as increases in COD (chemical oxygen demand) and decreases in transparency, was quantitatively assessed as corresponding to an increase in air temperature. In addition, we found that higher precipitation led to high nitrogen concentrations on a monthly basis, as well as on a yearly basis, probably induced by both the runoff of soilwater having high concentrations and the lowering of residence times of lake water.Climate change effects on water quality in Lake Kasumigaura, Japan, were studies using 17 yr of monitoring data. The Difference from the Previous Year method was used to account for watershed changes (e.g., land use, population, etc.) in analyzing air temperature-water temperature relationships. This relationship was influenced by the amount of yearly precipitation. Lake water quality deterioration appeared to correspond to increased air temperature. Higher precipitation led to high nitrogen concentrations (on monthly and yearly scales), probably because of soil water runoff having high nitrogen levels and because of shorter lake water residence times.","DPY method; Global warming; Lake water quality; Statistical prediction","Difference from the previous year (DPY) method; Atmospheric temperature; Chemical oxygen demand; Eutrophication; Global warming; Meteorology; Nitrogen; Precipitation (meteorology); Runoff; Statistical methods; Transparency; Water quality; Lakes; climate change; eutrophic environment; forecasting method; global warming; hydrological response; lake water; statistical analysis; water quality; Japan",,,,,,"Clair, T.A., Ehrman, J.M., Variations in discharge and dissolved organic carbon and nitrogen export from terrestrial basins with changes in climate: A neural network approach (1996) Limnology and Oceanography, 41, pp. 921-927; Ebise, S., Storm runoff loading of nutrients and pollutants in upper rivers (1991) Japan Journal of Limnology, 52, pp. 241-253; Fee, E.J., Hecky, R.E., Kasian, S.E.M., Cruikshank, D.R., Effects of lake size, water clarity, and climatic variability on mixing depths in Canadian Shield lakes (1996) Limnology and Oceanography, 41, pp. 912-920; Fukushima, T., Muraoka, K., Current and vertical mixing in a shallow lake (1981) Verhandlungen Internationale Vereinigung Limnologie, 21, pp. 141-149; Fukushima, T., Harasawa, H., Carrying capacity and vulnerability of four 